          header
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=F8CAFD10-50A3-4EFF-A518-805D9740736F&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fdevon-archer-testimony-house-oversight-james-comer-hunter-biden-joe-biden-8bc222ca&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption">亨特·拜登的前商业伙伴德文·阿彻 (Devon Archer) 向众议院监督委员会闭门作证，讲述总统与其子的海外商业交易的关系，其中包括与商业伙伴通过免提电话进行了 20 多次通话。图片：路透社/美联社 综合：马克·凯利<span class="imageCredit">华尔街日报互动版</span></p></div></div><p>所有人都知道，亨特·拜登与乌克兰和中国的能源公司合作开展利润丰厚的工作时，并没有出售他在能源市场的专业知识。但他卖的是什么？亨特的前商业伙伴德文·阿彻周一提供的答案是拜登的“品牌”。</p><div class="media-object scope-web,mobileapps
          wrap
"></div><p>阿彻先生向众议院监督委员会闭门作证，我们正在等待笔录以查看他的完整证词。但根据监督委员会主席詹姆斯·科默发布的一份摘要，阿彻先生证实亨特正在宣传拜登家族的名字及其所暗示的政治机会。</p><p>考虑到我们已经了解到亨特·拜登与乌克兰能源公司 Burisma 和中国华信能源公司的合作，这并不奇怪。阿彻先生告诉委员会，亨特在商务会议期间让当时担任副总裁的父亲开免提电话超过 20 次，以推销“品牌”。</p><p>据科默先生的说法，阿彻先生认为，丑闻缠身的“如果没有‘品牌’，Burisma 就会倒闭”。科默表示，由于与拜登的关系，“人们会害怕合法地扰乱布里斯马公司”。</p><p>阿彻还证实，Burisma 高管向亨特施加了巨大压力，要求他利用他的关系来处理前乌克兰检察官维克托·肖金 (Viktor Shokin) 对公司的调查。乔·拜登公开宣称自己解雇了肖金，理由是调查腐败的检察官本人也腐败。</p><p>科默先生说，阿彻先生还告诉委员会，乔·拜登亲自参加了亨特在北京和华盛顿特区与中国和俄罗斯商人举行的其他商务会议。这与拜登总统声称他从未与儿子讨论过这些商业往来的说法相悖。</p><p>听取证词的民主党人丹·戈德曼 (Dan Goldman) 表示，阿彻先生告诉委员会，拜登夫妇从未在这些电话中讨论过业务，因此证词毫无意义。但亨特不太可能想和他的父亲谈论天气。他知道自己在卖什么，随着众议院的不断寻找，我们将看到我们还了解到什么。</p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Mon, 31 Jul 2023 22:41:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/devon-archer-testimony-house-oversight-james-comer-hunter-biden-joe-biden-8bc222ca</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/devon-archer-testimony-house-oversight-james-comer-hunter-biden-joe-biden-8bc222ca<author><![CDATA[The Editorial Board]]></author><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>内容类型</category><category>评论/意见</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>德文郡弓箭手</category><category>詹姆斯·科默</category><category>乔·拜登</category><category>亨特·拜登</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>政治</category><category>国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>内容类型</category><category>评论</category><category>意见</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[The Yellow Road to Bankruptcy]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>高昂的劳动力和债务成本拖垮了这家历史悠久的货运公司。 <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB12070190061687823722304590121831577123938"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB12070190061687823722304590121831577123938"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/editorial-board" itemprop="url" rel="author">编委会</a></span>撰文</div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 7 月 31 日下午 6:41 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/yellow-bankruptcy-trucking-teamsters-sean-obrien-labor-1cb92273"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-827104?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> 7 月 31 日，拉斯维加斯，Yellow Corp. 的一个工厂停放着拖车，该工厂在该货运公司停止所有运营后关闭。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：帕特里克·T.法伦/法新社/盖蒂图片社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>今年，当陷入困境的<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/YELL" class="">Yellow</a> <span class="company-name-type">Corp.</span>向工会员工寻求财务让步时，卡车司机协会主席肖恩·奥布莱恩 (Sean O&#39;Brien) 拒绝了，并在推特上发布了墓地里一块刻有“Yellow”字样的墓碑的图片。恭喜你，奥布莱恩先生。这家卡车运输公司周日表示，正准备申请破产，大约 22,000 名卡车司机可能会失业。</p><p>拥有 99 年历史的 Yellow 是美国第三大零担运输公司，将多个客户的货物集中在一辆拖车上。 1980 年国会放松对该行业的管制后，卡车运输业的竞争变得更加激烈。然而，Yellow 与卡车司机协会的劳工协议使其与非工会竞争对手的竞争力下降。</p><p> 2000 年代初，Yellow 利用廉价融资收购竞争对手。但在 2008 年金融恐慌期间，沉重的债务负担几乎使其破产。债权人以债务换股，但黄公司高昂的劳动力成本继续拖累其业绩。损失不断增加。 Yellow 于 2019 年在 6 亿美元贷款的帮助下再次进行重组。</p><p>然后大流行来袭。 Yellow 的投机信用评级使其无法利用美联储的企业信贷便利。在国会游说下，特朗普政府向耶洛提供了 7 亿美元的低成本“国家安全贷款”，用于支付养老金、医疗保健费用和资本投资。</p><p>民主党人现在批评特朗普政府滥用《关怀法案》的国家安全贷款计划。但正如国会监督委员会 6 月份的一份报告指出的那样，“每当国会向行政部门提供数十亿纳税人资金以及发放这些资金的巨大自由裁量权时，行政部门就很难抗拒这样做的冲动，这是可以理解的。”</p><p>游说这笔贷款的国会议员担心黄色破产将加速卡车司机协会中央各州多雇主养老基金的死亡螺旋。 Yellow 是该计划中最大的雇主之一。</p><p>在黄色获得财政部贷款后，卡车司机们阻止了公司降低劳动力成本的努力。随着今年卡车运输量的下降，Yellow 难以支付其健康和养老金义务。该公司还有 17.5 亿美元的债务将在未来一年半内到期，在信贷条件收紧的情况下，这些债务将难以再融资。 7 月中旬，当卡车司机工会威胁要罢工时，黄色顾客纷纷逃离。随后其财务状况迅速恶化，最终破产。</p><p>奥布莱恩先生可能后来才意识到自己玩得太过头了。黄的麻烦可能是他上周决定达成新协议以避免<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/UPS" class="">联合包裹服务公司</a>罢工的一个原因<span class="company-name-type">。</span>尽管耶洛失败了，但由于拜登政府去年向中央各州基金提供了 360 亿美元的救助，卡车司机工会的养老金还是有保障的。一个问题是，养老金救助是否鼓励卡车司机们对黄色不留情面。</p><p>这家货运公司的倒闭再次提醒我们，合并并不总是成功，尤其是那些债务堆积的合并。尽管美联储的货币政策正常化可能会导致企业伤亡，但它也会将投资引导至管理更好的企业。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=308CC4D2-8328-495D-966C-0055C8060126&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fyellow-bankruptcy-trucking-teamsters-sean-obrien-labor-1cb92273&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption">期刊编辑报告：玛丽·奥格雷迪 (Mary O&#39;Grady)、比尔·麦格恩 (Bill McGurn)、阿莉西亚·芬利 (Alysia Finley) 和金·斯特拉塞尔 (Kim Strassel) 分享了本周最好和最差的内容。图片：盖蒂图片社/罗阿诺克时报，美联社综合报道：马克·凯利<span class="imageCredit">《华尔街日报》互动版</span></p></div></div></section></div></main></div>]]>;</description><pubDate> Mon, 31 Jul 2023 22:41:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/yellow-bankruptcy-trucking-teamsters-sean-obrien-labor-1cb92273</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/yellow-bankruptcy-trucking-teamsters-sean-obrien-labor-1cb92273<author><![CDATA[The Editorial Board]]></author><category>卡车运输</category><category>货运/物流</category><category>陆路运输</category><category>运输/物流</category><category>破产</category><category>劳工/人事</category><category>企业行动</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>企业财务困难</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>内容类型</category><category>评论/意见</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>黄色的</category><category>叫喊</category><category>卡车司机</category><category>破产</category><category>劳动</category><category>人员</category><category>企业行动</category><category>公司的</category><category>行业新闻</category><category>企业财务困难</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>政治</category><category>国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>内容类型</category><category>评论</category><category>意见</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>卡车运输</category><category>货运</category><category>后勤</category><category>陆路运输</category><category>运输</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Nigel Farage Shows What Happens When Good Banks Go Woke]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>英国的一桩丑闻显示了金融武器化的实际情况。 <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB12770427345856314244904590122021070373774"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB12770427345856314244904590122021070373774"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/editorial-board" itemprop="url" rel="author">编委会</a></span>撰文</div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 7 月 31 日下午 6:40 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/coutts-bank-u-k-nigel-farage-alison-rose-peter-flavel-a31c7f31"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-827106?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">奈杰尔·法拉奇</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：亚历克斯·布兰登/美联社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>这是你在美国几乎没有听说过的最大的金融丑闻：两名英国银行高管失去了工作，其他人可能也会因关闭客户账户的政治化决定而引起轩然大波。这对美国人来说是一个警示故事，告诉他们当优秀银行醒来时会发生什么。</p><p>顾资银行 (Coutts &amp; Co.) 的混乱始于 6 月底，当时奈杰尔·法拉奇 (Nigel Farage) 表示，这家独家私人银行将关闭他的账户。法拉奇先生是英国著名右翼政治家，是 2016 年英国脱欧公投的主要推动者，并在此前后表达了经济和社会保守观点。</p><p>法拉奇声称，他因政治原因而被取消银行业务，但该银行最初否认了这一说法。顾资银行母公司 NatWest 的首席执行官艾莉森·罗斯 (Alison Rose) 告诉 BBC 记者，法拉奇先生的最低余额要求低于顾资银行的高额要求。</p><p>事实证明法拉奇先生是对的。他获得了一份 40 页的银行内部讨论记录副本，内容涉及他的账户。顾资银行员工得出的结论是，继续为法拉奇先生提供银行服务将为顾资银行带来“重大声誉风险”，因为他有时在种族关系、俄罗斯和气候政策等问题上发表煽动性言论。档案记录员工承认，以其他方式保留法拉奇先生的账户是有商业理由的。</p><p>罗斯女士承认自己是 BBC 报道的消息来源后被迫辞职，该报道最初将泄密事件归咎于匿名消息来源。几天后，顾资银行首席执行官彼得·弗拉维尔（Peter Flavel）也跟进了此事，这是该银行试图从丑闻中恢复过来的一部分。总理里希·苏纳克正在考虑新的规定，以防止银行因客户的政治观点而将其拒之门外。</p><p>这个故事不仅仅是一场英国商业混乱，因为发生在顾资银行法拉奇先生身上的事情也可能发生在美国。随着新证据表明拜登政府与科技公司之间存在密切联系，以压制政治上不受欢迎的观点，美国也卷入了有关新冠病毒大流行的社交媒体审查丑闻。高管们知道政客和监管机构对其企业拥有巨大的权力，这增加了他们接受审查的动力。</p><p>出于类似的原因，大西洋两岸的金融机构都宣扬其自由主义文化信念，库茨关闭法拉奇先生账户的部分理由是，为他提供服务将“与我们作为包容性组织的立场相悖”。档案。</p><p>银行受到如此严格的监管，以至于它们在商业决策中不可避免地要考虑政治因素。 2008 年获得救助后，英国纳税人仍持有国民西敏寺银行 39% 的股份，人们普遍预计左翼工党将赢得明年的选举。在档案中，库茨银行的员工没有公开考虑过他们可能很快就会受到反对法拉奇先生的政客的监管，但很难想象有人没有想到过这种想法。</p><p>随着政治家更加依赖银行来实施他们的政策，这种危险将会加剧。如果银行面临华盛顿推动气候议程的压力，它会为净零气候政策的批评者保留账户吗？</p><p>普通企业可以选择客户，但银行已经很长时间没有成为普通企业了。左派尤其将银行视为公用事业。法拉奇事件暴露了这种情况的危险性，而且不仅仅是在英国。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=34FABCBA-64BF-4342-BE51-E7CF2E50F2C5&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fcoutts-bank-u-k-nigel-farage-alison-rose-peter-flavel-a31c7f31&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption">仙境：美国19个州总检察长致函摩根大通，指责其歧视保守宗教团体。银行否认。美国的商业应该再次成为商业，而不是政治（05/17/23）。图片：Zuma Press/彭博新闻 综合：Mark Kelly<span class="imageCredit">华尔街日报互动版</span></p></div></div></section></div></main></div>]]>;</description><pubDate> Mon, 31 Jul 2023 22:40:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/coutts-bank-uk-nigel-farage-alison-rose-peter-flavel-a31c7f31</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/coutts-bank-uk-nigel-farage-alison-rose-peter-flavel-a31c7f31<author><![CDATA[The Editorial Board]]></author><category>银行业</category><category>商业银行</category><category>金融投资服务</category><category>银行/信贷</category><category>金融服务</category><category>投资/证券</category><category>私人银行/财富管理</category><category>法规/政府政策</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>内容类型</category><category>评论/意见</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>库茨</category><category>奈杰尔·法拉奇</category><category>彼得·弗拉维尔</category><category>艾莉森·罗斯</category><category>规定</category><category>政府政策</category><category>公司的</category><category>行业新闻</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>政治</category><category>国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>内容类型</category><category>评论</category><category>意见</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>银行业</category><category>商业银行</category><category>金融投资服务</category><category>信用</category><category>金融服务</category><category>投资</category><category>证券</category><category>私人银行</category><category>财富管理</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Devon Archer Throws a Curve]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>乔·拜登对亨特及其笔记本电脑的否认现已被证实。他会在 2024 年总统辩论中说什么？ <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB12070190061687823722304590122243035880462"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB12070190061687823722304590122243035880462"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="columnist_mini"> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/william-mcgurn"><img width="45" height="45" src="https://s.wsj.net/public/resources/images/B3-BI560_mcgurn_AM_20180807122138.jpg" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></a></div><div class="byline"> <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/william-mcgurn" itemprop="url" rel="author">威廉·麦格恩</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 7 月 31 日下午 6:22 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/devon-archer-throws-a-curve-house-testimony-plea-deal-debate-biden-d5b85171"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-826813?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">乔·拜登 7 月 27 日在华盛顿发表讲话。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：乔纳森·恩斯特/路透社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>到目前为止，关于乔·拜登和 2024 年的最大问题是他是否能身体健康地参加辩论。但在亨特认罪失败后，亨特·拜登前商业伙伴德文·阿彻周一在众议院监督委员会作了闭门证词，引发了另一个问题：总统是否需要为在 2020 年辩论期间误导公众而道歉，当时他明确表示否认儿子海外权谋？</p><div class="media-object scope-web,mobileapps
          wrap
"></div><p>如果亨特的认罪协议没有在联邦法院破裂，这一切都会消失。检察官告诉法庭，亨特可能仍会被指控未注册为外国代理人。</p><p>然后是阿彻先生周一的证词。根据董事长詹姆斯·科默的一份声明，阿彻先生作证说，乔·拜登加入了与亨特客户、乌克兰能源巨头布里斯马公司的电话交谈，以“出售该品牌”。阿切尔先生进一步表示，布里斯马向亨特施压，要求他就检察官维克托·肖金(Viktor Shokin)的问题向“华盛顿特区”寻求帮助，而副总统拜登曾推动解雇他。</p><p>这并不能证明乔·拜登讨论了商业条款或分享了任何利润。但至少，它暴露了拜登在2020年对美国人民的操纵。</p><p>亨特在两次总统辩论中都占据了显着位置，因为<a href="https://www.wsj.com/topics/person/donald-trump">唐纳德·特朗普</a>不断提到他。第一次提及是在 9 月 29 日于克利夫兰举行的辩论中。在拜登先生批评特朗普总统的对华政策后，现任总统表示：</p><p> “中国吃了你的午餐，乔。难怪你儿子进去了，哇——他拿出了数十亿美元。他拿出数十亿美元来管理。他赚了数百万美元。而且，在我们讨论的过程中，为什么莫斯科市长的妻子只是出于好奇而给了你儿子 350 万美元？”</p><p>然后他问道：“他对布里斯马做了什么？”</p><p>拜登总共八次宣称“这不是真的”或类似的言论。他七次表示特朗普的主张“不可信”，有时“完全不可信”。接近尾声时，他补充道：“我儿子在布里斯马没有做错任何事。”</p><p>特朗普先生不会就此罢休：亨特“在乌克兰、中国、莫斯科和其他地方发了财”。拜登再次否认：“这根本不是真的。”</p><p>拜登指望媒体能够继续前进，而事实也基本上做到了。但随后拜登夫妇与玛丽莲·诺雷卡法官发生了冲突。她向亨特·拜登本人证实，与他父亲的说法相反，他确实从乌克兰和中国公司获得了一小笔财富。</p><p>然后是特朗普反复提及的 2014 年莫斯科前市长遗孀埃琳娜·巴图琳娜 (Elena Baturina) 的 350 万美元电汇。亨特的律师表示，他的客户对接收公司没有兴趣，也不是该公司的联合创始人。但阿彻先生与该公司有联系，而且他也知道亨特的交易是如何构建的。也许我们会从文字记录中了解更多信息。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4>了解更多 大街</h4><p></p><ul class="articleList"><li><a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/hunter-biden-joe-bargain-plea-tax-irs-whistleblower-archer-ziegler-shapley-burisma-5f891342?mod=article_relatedinline" target="_self" class="icon none">亨特·拜登的讨价还价请求</a><span class="date">2023 年 7 月 24 日</span></li><li><a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/no-labels-equals-trump-manchin-lieberman-2024-election-biden-rematch-55feda8e?mod=article_relatedinline" target="_self" class="icon none">“无标签”等于特朗普？</a> <span class="date">2023 年 7 月 17 日</span></li><li><a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-ongoing-investigation-dodge-hunter-biden-david-weiss-bribe-question-informant-67c31868?mod=article_relatedinline" target="_self" class="icon none">针对亨特·拜登的“正在进行的调查”道奇</a><span class="date">2023 年 7 月 10 日</span></li></ul></div></div><p>拜登在 10 月 22 日的第二场辩论中继续表示绝对否认。特朗普再次不肯罢休。 “如果俄罗斯、乌克兰、中国、其他国家、伊拉克的情况属实，那么他就是一个腐败的政客，”他说。特朗普随后提到了“来自地狱的笔记本电脑”，促使拜登暗示这不是亨特的。</p><p> “你看，”他说，“有 50 名前国家情报人员说，他指控我的这件事是俄罗斯的计划。他们说这具有所有特征——四、五名中央情报局前负责人，双方都说他所说的是一堆垃圾。”</p><p>这也是不真实的。拜登援引的“50 名前国家情报人员”确实暗示这台笔记本电脑可能是俄罗斯的虚假信息。但我们现在知道这台笔记本电脑是亨特的，而前情报官员就是散布虚假信息的人。</p><p>简而言之，拜登先生在辩论中没有说出有关亨特的真相，今天也没有办法为这些答案辩护。在明年选举前夕，随着国会调查的继续，我们可能会了解到更多信息。</p><p>就连拜登政府也承认总统的全面否认不再可信。毫无疑问这就是新闻秘书的原因</p>卡琳·让-皮埃尔最近将党的官方路线从“总统从未与他讨论过他儿子的生意”改为“总统从未与他有过生意”。<p></p><p>拜登在 2024 年辩论中面临的真正危险是，这位共和党候选人是否会问他一个显而易见的问题：“拜登先生。”主席先生，自 2020 年以来我们了解到，您上次登上辩论舞台时所声称的有关您儿子海外业务的几乎所有内容都是不真实的。为什么美国人民现在应该相信你所说的一切？”</p><p><em>写信至 mcgurn@wsj.com。</em> </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=F8CAFD10-50A3-4EFF-A518-805D9740736F&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fdevon-archer-throws-a-curve-house-testimony-plea-deal-debate-biden-d5b85171&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption">亨特·拜登的前商业伙伴德文·阿彻 (Devon Archer) 向众议院监督委员会闭门作证，讲述总统与其子的海外商业交易的关系，其中包括与商业伙伴通过免提电话进行了 20 多次通话。图片：路透社/美联社 综合：马克·凯利<span class="imageCredit">华尔街日报互动版</span></p></div></div></section></div></main></div>]]>;</description><pubDate> Mon, 31 Jul 2023 22:22:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/devon-archer-throws-a-curve-house-testimony-plea-deal-debate-biden-d5b85171</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/devon-archer-throws-a-curve-house-testimony-plea-deal-debate-biden-d5b85171<author><![CDATA[William McGurn]]></author><category>猎人</category><category>中国</category><category>乌克兰</category><category>笔记本电脑</category><category>对外交易</category><category>辩论阶段</category><category>见证</category><category>总统</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>选举</category><category>国家/总统选举</category><category>内容类型</category><category>评论/意见</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>亨特·拜登</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>政治</category><category>国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>选举</category><category>国家的</category><category>总统选举</category><category>内容类型</category><category>评论</category><category>意见</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[The Delicate U.S. Task of Courting India]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>这两个截然不同的民主国家仅通过共同语言部分地结合在一起。 <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB11490979256760064080404590116542526869312"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB11490979256760064080404590116542526869312"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="columnist_mini"> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/walter-russell-mead"><img width="45" height="45" src="https://s.wsj.net/public/resources/images/B3-BS043_Mead_W_AM_20180912115022.jpg" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></a></div><div class="byline"> <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/walter-russell-mead" itemprop="url" rel="author">沃尔特·拉塞尔·米德</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 7 月 31 日下午 6:21 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-delicate-us-task-of-courting-india-bjp-human-rights-coordination-china-b10d8650"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-826794?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCredit">照片：爱德华多·穆尼奥斯/路透社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p><em>新德里</em></p><p>印度预计到本十年末将超过德国和日本成为<a href="https://www.cnbc.com/2022/12/01/india-to-leapfrog-to-third-largest-economy-by-2030.html" target="_blank" class="icon none">世界第三大经济体</a>，让印度走上正轨已成为美国政策制定者的一项关键任务。</p><p>但与执政的印度人民党结盟的政治、宗教和商界领袖进行了一周的会谈，这提醒我这种关系有多么困难。美国和印度都是民主国家。他们都渴望在不发生战争的情况下抵消中国在亚洲的影响力。但这两个社会之间的差异是巨大的。维持这种关系需要技巧、耐心和理解。</p><p>大多数美国人对印度有很多不了解的地方，而且很少有美国人足够了解印度，能够向我们其他人解释它。印度的民主比美国的民主更为复杂和混乱，印度生活的元素包括社区暴力、对资本主义和美国的本能怀疑、愤怒、困惑和挫败试图参与其中的美国人。</p><p>在现任印度人民党政府的领导下，印度当局采取了一些有争议的措施。 <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/indian-opposition-leader-rahul-gandhi-expelled-from-parliament-e08028f0?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">反对党领袖拉胡尔·甘地</a>在一项相对较小的法律调查后被剥夺了议会席位。印度官员利用税法骚扰从<a href="https://www.ft.com/content/ee2b8b03-315b-4074-acac-173b8c2e7124" target="_blank" class="icon none">知名智囊团</a>（政策研究中心）到英国广播公司（BBC）等批评者，并限制印度非政府组织（包括基督教团体）从国外接受资金的能力。当局有时对宗教少数群体对暴力袭击或歧视性国家立法的投诉反应迟缓。</p><p>政府和政党官员认为，印度的现实很复杂。他们声称甘地先生的强制退出是一个司法问题，州而不是联邦当局对许多困扰国际人权组织的决定负有责任，而印度人民党政治对手领导下的过去政府也做过同样的事情，甚至更糟。他们提出了一些正确的观点，但来自美国人权组织的批评声音仍在不断增加。</p><p>除非双方明智地处理，这样的问题可能会破坏外交关系。美国对民主倒退的本能反应——高尚的说教和制裁威胁的结合——激怒了印度人，他们对美国美德的怀疑根深蒂固。任何印度政府都不能承受屈服于外国要求的后果。</p><p>印度人对于美国的虚伪和傲慢有时是正确的。美国人有时对印度政策的误导是正确的。即便如此，两国也必须共同努力。我们需要找到解决敏感问题的方法，以便将重点放在团结我们的更大利益上。</p><p>这就是美国缺乏真正的印度专业知识造成问题的地方。过去30年里，有数十万美国年轻人在中国生活和学习，但只有少数人去了印度。学习印度语言的人甚至更少。 While many educated Indians speak English, a large majority do not comfortably read or write in it, and without access to the vernacular press and public, American ideas about Indian politics and culture are inevitably skewed. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4> Read More Global View</h4><p></p><ul class="articleList"><li> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-movement-shaping-a-modern-india-rss-modi-hindu-nationalism-e70586d9?mod=article_relatedinline" target="_self" class="icon none">The Movement Shaping a Modern India</a> <span class="date">July 24, 2023</span></li><li> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/chinas-economy-hits-the-skids-slow-growth-real-estate-trade-peace-us-unemployment-5b38d155?mod=article_relatedinline" target="_self" class="icon none">China&#39;s Economy Hits the Skids</a> <span class="date">July 17, 2023</span></li><li> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/its-too-early-to-count-putin-out-prigozhin-wagner-mutiny-defense-asset-cf7d98e3?mod=article_relatedinline" target="_self" class="icon none">It&#39;s Too Early to Count Putin Out</a> <span class="date">June 26, 2023</span></li></ul></div></div><p> During the Cold War, Americans and our principal allies understood that the Atlantic Community and the US-Japan relationship needed people-to-people ties to become enduring and strong. Governments funded language-study programs and promoted exchanges. Civil-society groups ranging from Rotary clubs and local chambers of commerce to universities and foundations joined in a prolonged effort to build the West into a community. This wasn&#39;t always easy in the wake of World War II—American relationships with Germany and Japan were not exactly love matches.</p><p> Building the US-India relationship will take at least as much work. While India already sends <a href="https://in.usembassy.gov/the-united-states-remains-a-top-choice-for-indian-students-pursuing-higher-education-abroad-open-doors-report-2/" target="_blank" class="icon none">hundreds of thousands of students</a> to American universities, and the Indian-American community operates effectively as ambassadors and interpreters between the two cultures, a much broader engagement is needed.</p><p> Government can do its part. Washington should step up funding for the study of Indian languages and history. It should simplify the process for issuing visas to Indian scholars, journalists and businesspeople and work with Indian officials to promote cooperation between universities and other civil-society groups in the two countries.</p><p> But government action alone won&#39;t be enough. A generation of young Americans needs to study and live in India, learning local languages and cultures. Programs bringing young Americans to India to teach English while learning about Indian culture and history would help both countries. Businesses should invest in deepening the ties that will enable the economic relationship between the two countries to reach its full potential. Philanthropy needs to make the relationship a priority, providing universities and think tanks with the resources to build up their India-focused programs.</p><p> Deepening our relationship with India enhances American security and promotes American economic growth. Investing in that relationship should be one of our highest national priorities. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=308CC4D2-8328-495D-966C-0055C8060126&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fthe-delicate-us-task-of-courting-india-bjp-human-rights-coordination-china-b10d8650&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption">期刊编辑报告：玛丽·奥格雷迪 (Mary O&#39;Grady)、比尔·麦格恩 (Bill McGurn)、阿莉西亚·芬利 (Alysia Finley) 和金·斯特拉塞尔 (Kim Strassel) 分享了本周最好和最差的内容。图片：盖蒂图片社/罗阿诺克时报，美联社综合报道：马克·凯利<span class="imageCredit">《华尔街日报》互动版</span></p></div></div></section></div></main></div>]]>;</description><pubDate> Mon, 31 Jul 2023 22:21:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-delicate-us-task-of-courting-india-bjp-human-rights-coordination-china-b10d8650</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-delicate-us-task-of-courting-india-bjp-human-rights-coordination-china-b10d8650<author><![CDATA[Walter Russell Mead]]></author><category>印度</category><category>bjp</category><category> human rights</category><category>中国</category><category>asia</category><category> sanctions</category><category> universities</category><category> lecture</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>国际关系</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>内容类型</category><category>Commentaries/Opinions</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>国际关系</category><category>政治</category><category>国内政治</category><category>内容类型</category><category>commentaries</category><category> opinions</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[FDR Made the Depression Great Again]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> How the blue eagle, symbol of a 1933 law, had its wings clipped. <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB12423497912280243653204590084423513540294"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB12423497912280243653204590084423513540294"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name">Jason Taylor</span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> July 31, 2023 6:20 pm ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/fdr-made-the-depression-great-again-nira-blue-eagle-output-economy-5cae29e"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-826542?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> A badge demonstrating support for the National Recovery Administration created in 1933 by President Franklin D. Roosevelt.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Getty Images</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> An exotic bird landed on American soil 90 years ago Tuesday. At first the public celebrated the Blue Eagle emblem, symbol of President Franklin Roosevelt&#39;s ambitious agenda to improve the economy. The eagle became ubiquitous in store fronts, advertisements and movie trailers. In September 1933, 1.5 million people lined the streets of New York City for a nine-hour Blue Eagle parade.</p><p> But few mourned when the bird was scrapped after two years. Instead of working its promised wonders, that “buzzard,” as Henry Ford called it, helped put the “Great” in the Great Depression.</p><p> The tragedy is that during Roosevelt&#39;s first months in office the US economy made tremendous strides. Between March and July 1933, employment, production and spending all increased sharply. The nation seemed to be on a highway to recovery, largely thanks to Roosevelt&#39;s policies.</p><p> But what good policy giveth, bad policy taketh away. In June 1933 Roosevelt signed the National Industrial Recovery Act (NIRA), which required firms to meet with competitors and construct a “code of fair competition.” Over two years, 557 codes were implemented in industries ranging from steel to fishing tackle.</p><p> These codes permitted collusive actions that would otherwise violate antitrust law. Businesses that were found violating the codes—say, charging a price below the code-specified one—could face hefty fines and imprisonment. For their membership in government-enforced cartels, firms were forced to raise hourly wages.</p><p> The Blue Eagle insignia, with its accompanying message, “We do our part,” was created to ensure compliance with the NIRA. Companies that violated the act&#39;s labor or cartel rules were barred from publicly displaying the Blue Eagle. FDR urged Americans to boycott them.</p><p> Predictably, the NIRA was a disaster. Companies responded to forced wage increases by scaling back employment. And colluding firms did what cartels generally do—they restricted output and raised prices.</p><p> While manufacturing output rose an unprecedented 78% between March and July 1933, it fell sharply after the Blue Eagle&#39;s arrival. By November two-thirds of the recovery gains were lost. Output didn&#39;t pick up until a year later, when business owners, irritated by the Blue Eagle, quit “doing their part” and openly violated the codes, overwhelming the enforcement offices.</p><p> By the time the Supreme Court ruled the NIRA unconstitutional in May 1935, even Roosevelt had acknowledged privately that this “whole thing is a mess.” After the Blue Eagle&#39;s demise, the nation&#39;s recovery resumed and manufacturing output rose 50% over the next 18 months.</p><p> While it&#39;s impossible to say exactly how the US economy would have fared without the NIRA&#39;s enactment, we do know one thing: The Great Depression would&#39;ve been a lot less depressing. As he signed the NIRA, FDR said it was “the most important and far-reaching legislation ever enacted.” It was important, far-reaching and disastrous.</p><p> <em>Mr. Taylor is an economic professor at Central Michigan University and author of “Deconstructing the Monolith: The Microeconomics of the National Industrial Recovery Act.”</em> </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=142AA7D8-F7CE-46CC-8C97-37E8E30612D1&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Ffdr-made-the-depression-great-again-nira-blue-eagle-output-economy-5cae29e&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption"> Wonder Land: Inspired by China and Saudi Arabia, Team Biden&#39;s vision for US industrial policy is one in which the government explicitly leads; everyone else follows. Images: AP/AFP/Getty Images Composite: Mark Kelly <span class="imageCredit">The Wall Street Journal Interactive Edition</span></p></div></div></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Mon, 31 Jul 2023 22:20:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/fdr-made-the-depression-great-again-nira-blue-eagle-output-economy-5cae29e</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/fdr-made-the-depression-great-again-nira-blue-eagle-output-economy-5cae29e<category> nira</category><category> wages</category><category> prices</category><category> competition</category><category> cartel</category><category> codes of competition</category><category> great depression</category><category> employment</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>内容类型</category><category>Commentaries/Opinions</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>观点</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>政治</category><category>国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>内容类型</category><category>commentaries</category><category> opinions</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>观点</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[‘The Science of Spin’ Review: The World in a Whirligig]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> From early on, humanity&#39;s key inventions involved rotation: grindstones, potter&#39;s wheels, treadmills, pumps. The wheel, though, has been overrated. <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB11754030163052123715304590112630365408848"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-826991?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCredit">照片：阿拉米库存照片</p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB11754030163052123715304590112630365408848"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name">James B. Meigs</span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> July 31, 2023 6:19 pm ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-science-of-spin-review-the-world-in-a-whirligig-6de2c75d"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p> More than a few authors have found success with books that look at a broad swath of history, ideas or science through the lens of a single topic. The trend might have begun with James Gleick&#39;s “Chaos” (1987), which explored the surprising role of randomness in nature. Less abstractly, Mark Kurlansky took a tight-focus approach in “Cod” (1997) and Mary Roach in “Stiff” (2003), a book about, of all things, cadavers.</p><p> Roland Ennos elevates this approach to dizzying heights in “The Science of Spin.” The notion that lots of things spin—everything from toy tops to hurricanes—might seem pedestrian. But Mr. Ennos, a professor of biological sciences at the University of Hull, wants us to understand that spin is fundamental. It plays a part in the functioning of our bodies and the design of our infrastructure. It can also, of course, be found in the orderly motion of our planet and, indeed, of the universe. Mr. Ennos hopes that “The Science of Spin” will enable readers to “finally be able to understand what really makes the world go round.” </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/schemas/84d92765-15f6-4564-8af6-e53178e52e85.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p> He begins by recounting how British engineers underestimated the power of spin when designing the groundbreaking Sopwith Camel biplane during World War I. In a traditional aircraft, the motor is mounted to the fuselage and spins a shaft with a propeller at one end. In the Camel,the shaft was locked to the airframe while the entire motor spun furiously, along with a conjoined propeller. This odd design had several advantages and one big disadvantage: The enormous rotational force of the motor tended to send inexperienced pilots into rapid death spirals.</p><p> Having chastened the reader not to take the physics of spin lightly, Mr. Ennos rewinds his story roughly to the beginning of time. We learn how the big bang “formed huge swirls in the clouds of gas that it produced.” The eddies acted as nuclei for the formation of stars, galaxies and all the rest. “Spin,” he writes, “is the very reason our universe is here at all.”</p><p> Mr. Ennos endeavors to persuade us—the Sopwith Camel episode aside—to be thankful that our universe has so much spinning in it. The chaotic cloud of gas that evolved into our orderly solar system could have done so only by spinning. We are particularly blessed by the way our home planet spins at just the right speed. Its rotation creates Earth&#39;s magnetic envelope, which keeps us safe from deadly solar radiation. On Earth&#39;s surface it seems that everything from the atmosphere to ocean currents is in a state of spin, constant mixing and stirring processes that moderate temperatures, reduce wind speeds and regulate rainfall. In short, spin makes the world “a marvelous place in which to live.”</p><p> Mr. Ennos really gets rolling when he describes how much of human flourishing through history has involved harnessing the power of spin. We learn how Paleolithic people used bow drills—wooden spindles that could be spun rapidly by a loosely strung bow—to start fires, drill the holes needed for making tools and even perform simple dentistry. Finding new ways to spin things made early civilization possible: Winding cotton and wool fibers into thread allowed us to start wearing fabrics instead of animal skins. Long before the Industrial Revolution, humanity&#39;s crucial inventions usually involved rotation: grindstones, potter&#39;s wheels, treadmills and all manner of pumps.</p><p> Not that Mr. Ennos&#39;s story is simple tech triumphalism. Contrarians especially will enjoy his account of what he calls “the underwhelming wheel.” People often regard the invention of the wheel as the paradigm of a world-changing innovation. In fact, Mr. Ennos says, wheels—at least the kinds used for transportation—weren&#39;t all that useful through most of human history. Before the development of engineered roads, the ground was just too rough to make wheeled transport much of an improvement over walking or riding on horseback. The Incas, Mayans and Aztecs created toys that rolled on four wheels, Mr. Ennos notes, but they never created adult-size versions. Without metal tools, it wasn&#39;t possible to make durable wheels out of wood.</p><p> The pace of Mr. Ennos&#39;s narrative quickens with the advent of the Industrial Revolution. Water wheels power cotton gins and weaving machines, and turbines spin faster still. Steam engines evolve year by year as an increasingly mobile power source, until steam is supplanted by diesel and gasoline. Trying to keep up may leave some readers&#39; heads, well, spinning.</p><p> Mr. Ennos&#39;s final chapters explore the ways in which humans embody rotational mechanics in work and leisure. We see how pitchers and golfers wind up before unspooling as much energy as possible into the balls they put in play. Mr. Ennos wants us to understand the human body as a sort of machine, one with hinges and levers that amplify rotational forces. Our “complex jointed bodies,” he says, are in many ways superior to mechanical systems.</p><p> “The Science of Spin” moves too fast to spend much time getting to know the people behind the story. When Mr. Ennos discusses figure skating, for instance—a sport that seems to be almost nothing but spin—he breaks down what happens when a skater pulls in her arms to accelerate rotation. The physics are fascinating. But one wishes that he had interviewed a figure skater to ask: How does it feel?</p><p> Mr. Ennos closes by bemoaning the fact that many scientists lack an “intuitive feel for the science of spin.” Too often, he says, they turn to equations to model the behavior of spinning objects when they should start with close observation. School children, he argues, should be given more time to experiment with tops and gyroscopes. These simple toys can teach us about the beautifully balanced, dynamic nature of our universe. And, whether we are tossing a Frisbee or designing an airplane, that&#39;s something we should all take a little time to appreciate.</p><p> <em>Mr. Meigs is the former editor of Popular Mechanics and a senior fellow at the Manhattan Institute.</em></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Mon, 31 Jul 2023 22:19:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-science-of-spin-review-the-world-in-a-whirligig-6de2c75d</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-science-of-spin-review-the-world-in-a-whirligig-6de2c75d<category>纺织品</category><category>Clothing/Textiles</category><category> Consumer Goods</category><category>图书</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>艺术/娱乐</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 排除过滤器</category><category>评论</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>观点</category><category>books</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>艺术</category><category>娱乐</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>c&amp;e 排除过滤器</category><category>评论</category><category>观点</category><category>textiles</category><category> clothing</category><category> consumer goods </category></item><item><title><![CDATA[‘Utopia’ by Travis Scott Review: Leaning In to Hip-Hop Spectacle]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> A high point on the rap calendar, the artist&#39;s first album since 2018 features a psychedelic sound, his signature vocals and major guests like Beyoncé, Drake and the Weeknd. <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="SB12070190061687823722304590122123270646584"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-826622?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Travis Scott performing in Miami</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Getty Images for E11EVEN </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="SB12070190061687823722304590122123270646584"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name">Mark Richardson</span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> July 31, 2023 5:42 pm ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/utopia-by-travis-scott-review-leaning-in-to-hip-hop-spectacle-1ea47138"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p> Travis Scott was a divisive figure in the rap world even before the 2021 tragedy at his hometown Astroworld Festival in Houston, in which a crowd-crush incident during his set led to 10 deaths and hundreds of injuries. Though Mr. Scott—born Jacques Webster in 1991—was enormously popular, with two No. 1 studio albums and four No. 1 singles, his rapid rise was often greeted with skepticism by hip-hop aficionados, who felt that his music was light on substance and that his lyrics had little to say. He was further criticized for his reaction to the concert disaster after he offered a jumbled apology via video that didn&#39;t seem to match the gravity of the situation, and some believed that he bore personal responsibility, given his onstage encouragement of fan intensity. Though the rapper was never formally accused of wrongdoing, he&#39;s mostly kept a low profile in the two years since, contributing to a handful of singles by other artists.</p><p> That all changed last week with the announcement and release of “Utopia” (Cactus Jack/Epic), Mr. Scott&#39;s fourth studio album and the follow-up to his smash 2018 LP “Astroworld.” His timing is good. So far, 2023 has been short on “event” records in hip-hop, and as Rolling Stone reported early in July, it&#39;s been a weak year for the genre on the charts. Mr. Scott has a chance of single-handedly changing the narrative with a collection that is epic in terms of both its content—at 73 minutes it&#39;s quite long for a hip-hop record—and its star-studded guest list. “Utopia” is deliberately framed as a blockbuster, the kind of release every fan of the genre is forced to engage with. And while it won&#39;t do anything to change the minds of those who have questioned Mr. Scott&#39;s writing skill, it&#39;s a consistently strong and occasionally thrilling collection of songs.</p><p> Mr. Scott&#39;s two greatest assets are his taste in production and the resonance of his voice. Since the beginning of his career, he&#39;s expressed admiration for rock and pop artists with an experimental streak, such as Björk and Radiohead, and “Utopia,” like “Astroworld” before it, is packed with lushly psychedelic beats. Though dozens of producers, songwriters and guest vocalists appear on the record, Mr. Scott and studio collaborators, including Mike Dean (Kanye West, the Weeknd), have assembled the pieces into a coherent whole.</p><p> The first track, “Hyaena,” opens the set with a quaking bassline and drums that sound like a herd of cattle stomping over a smashed steel gate, and after effortless high-speed rapping from Mr. Scott it concludes with a sample from Funkadelic&#39;s “Maggot Brain.” Another early highlight, “Modern Jam,” is produced by Guy-Manuel de Homem-Christo, better known as one half of Daft Punk, and the sleekly minimal pulse is the perfect backdrop for Mr. Scott&#39;s melodic verses. The song is an “I&#39;m back!” statement, and he&#39;s not saying anything particularly profound—“Know it&#39;s been a year since I seen the road / Had me inside like I&#39;m on parole” is a representative couplet—but “Modern Jam” lives up to the billing of its title.</p><p> While Mr. Scott&#39;s limitations as a line-by-line lyricist and storyteller are clear, his voice is one of the most distinctive in rap this century. It&#39;s gravelly and slightly nasal at the same time, and it&#39;s both a deeply physical sound and one that lends itself well to electronic processing. This combination gives Mr. Scott&#39;s rapping a futuristic sheen, and he always comes across as “new” even when you listen to tracks from several years ago. That said, he tends to skim the surface when he raps and frequently makes the most obvious choices. On the fifth cut, “God&#39;s Country,” that means delivering lines like “Go Ted Bundy, then go home and play Al Bundy ” that are both clumsy and mean nothing in particular.</p><p> But while such groaners crop up regularly on “Utopia,” the album&#39;s sonic wonders provide balance. The gorgeous “My Eyes” features the voice and glitchy electronics of Justin Vernon of Bon Iver and an equally great cameo from soulful English singer Sampha on a song that conveys mournful resignation. And the menacing “Meltdown,” with an opening rap by Drake, has a progressive structure that feels like three tracks in one, as it moves from eerie string samples to the thick bass growl of rap subgenre drill and ends with a coda of strummed acoustic guitar. Beyoncé drops in for a fleet rap to open the brisk and jazzy “Delresto (Echoes)” and then switches to singing as Mr. Scott joins her while Mr. Vernon once again contributes vocals.</p><p> One reason rap is faltering on the charts is because regional scenes have been ascendant. Hip-hop today is a fragmented and fast-moving genre with innumerable variations based on geography and shared aesthetics, and a lot of the music is created at home by the young. “Utopia” is fun in part because it pushes forcefully against that lo-fi trend. It&#39;s a highly polished and sophisticated production that probably involved some expensive studio bills, never mind the cost of features by big names like the Weeknd, SZA and 21 Savage. Yes, it&#39;s too long and ultimately doesn&#39;t have a lot to say, but take a long drive with “Utopia” turned up loud and you&#39;ll understand why we&#39;ll probably be hearing tunes from it in public spaces for many months.</p><p class="articleTagLine"> —Mr. Richardson is the Journal&#39;s rock and pop music critic. Follow him on Twitter @MarkRichardson.</p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Mon, 31 Jul 2023 21:42:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/utopia-by-travis-scott-review-leaning-in-to-hip-hop-spectacle-1ea47138</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/utopia-by-travis-scott-review-leaning-in-to-hip-hop-spectacle-1ea47138<category>艺术评论</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>艺术/娱乐</category><category>Music</category><category> Calendar of Events</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 排除过滤器</category><category>IWE Filter</category><category>日常新闻</category><category>评论</category><category>艺术回顾</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>艺术</category><category>娱乐</category><category>音乐</category><category>calendar of events</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>c&amp;e 排除过滤器</category><category>iwe filter</category><category>常规新闻</category><category>评论</category></item></channel></rss>